here is my code for you, with angularjs


    $scope.textSize = function () {
        function getCharSize() {
            var $span = $("<span>", {text: "qwertyuiopasdfghjklzxcvbnm"});
            $('#terminal').append($span);
            var size = {
                width: $span.outerWidth()/24
                , height: $span.outerHeight()
            };
            $span.remove();
            return size;
        }
        function getwindowSize() {
            var e = window,
                a = 'inner';
            if (!('innerWidth' in window )) {
                a = 'client';
                e = document.documentElement || document.body;
            }
            return {width: e[a + 'Width'], height: e[a + 'Height']};
        }
        var charSize = getCharSize();
        var windowSize = getwindowSize();
        return {
            x: Math.floor(windowSize.width / charSize.width)
            , y: Math.floor(windowSize.height / charSize.height)
        };
    };
    var rc = $scope.textSize();
    var term = new Terminal({
        rows:rc.y,
        cols:rc.x,
        screenKeys: false,
        cursorBlink: false
    });

@csachs Okay, I've added support for this because `dict` supports it. But, I have to say I find this application absolutely bizarre. 

Out of curiosity: when on earth would you use this in an application context? Or is this just a case of making the data structure mathematically and philosophically complete?

I'll need you to alert me to other methods that you need to support this self-referential functionality because I'm at a loss as to where else it would be needed.

Yes, regarding DLIB it is only supposed to generate NVCC arch switches, nothing more.. in controlled way.

In default it generates code for Fermi, Maxwell, Pascal, Volta, etc. By this external parametrization via CUDA_GENERATION="Maxwell" for example it will generate code only for:
```
-gencode arch=compute_50,code=sm_50
-gencode arch=compute_52,code=sm_52
```

On top, if this parameter is not submitted, so CMake CUDA_GENERATION will set to AUTO mode and tries to execute following code on the fly:
```
#include <stdio.h>
int main()
{
    int count = 0;
    if (cudaSuccess != cudaGetDeviceCount(&count)){return -1;}
    if (count == 0) {return -1;}
    for (int device = 0; device < count; ++device)
    {
        cudaDeviceProp prop;
        if (cudaSuccess != cudaGetDeviceProperties(&prop, device)){ continue;}
        printf("%d.%d ", prop.major, prop.minor);
    }
    return 0;
}
```
The result of this should be major and minor version of architecture, for example 5.0. So again it should limit need for binary files to just specific architecture.

And it the end if value is not submitted by packaging system (Gentoo ebuild) and AUTO mode fails -> it is not end of days, as this will finally failover to generate simply all architectures. So no  one should be harm, only used for tuning.

I will fork dlib and test locally and come with final PR when it is ready.

