Hi Mottie

I think I find where the problem is in `tablesorter.widget-scroller.js` 

This block of code inside `setup` function. (My comment prefix with ******)

`                               .on( 'sortEnd filterEnd'.split( ' ' ).join( namespace + ' ' ), function( event ) {
					// Sorting, so scroll to top
					if ( event.type === 'sortEnd' && wo.scroller_upAfterSort ) {
						$tableWrap
							.scrollLeft( wo.scroller_saved[0] )
							.animate({ scrollTop : 0 }, 'fast', function() {
								wo.scroller_isBusy = false;  // ****** this assignment seems to happen too late.
							});
					} else if ( wo.scroller_fixedColumns ) {
						setTimeout( function() {
							// restore previous scroll position
							$tableWrap
								.scrollTop( wo.scroller_saved[1] )
								.scrollLeft( wo.scroller_saved[0] );
							tsScroller.updateFixed( c, wo );
						}, 0 );
					}
				})`

It seems `wo.scroller_isBusy` is set to false after `resize` function is being called. Which means `wo.scroller_calcWidth` array will never be populated on this occasion.

The reason why it only happens to my table, might be because my table is both massive and complicated to build with lots of dom elements.

At the moment, for the sake of building `wo.scroller_calcWidth` array, I call `resize` function in .animate callback like so

`                                               $tableWrap
							.scrollLeft( wo.scroller_saved[0] )
							.animate({ scrollTop : 0 }, 'fast', function() {
								wo.scroller_isBusy = false;  // ****** this assignment seems to happen too late.
                                                                tsScroller.resize( c, wo ); // ****** call resize function here so wo.scroller_calcWidth can get built.
							});`

, and will try to simplifying dom elements in my table to see if it'll work with tablesorter_widget-scroller.js without amending the original code. 

Please do let me know if you think this is not advisable or there's a better way of solving the issue.

Many thanks

Hi @getvivekv!

If you change the [`cssInfoBlock` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#cssinfoblock) (default is `"tablesorter-infoOnly"`) to `"avoid-sort"`, then no sort will be applied and the filter widget will ignore the contents of that tbody.

```js
$('table').tablesorter({
    cssInfoBlock: 'avoid-sort'
});
```

\* Please note that this will only work with the code from this fork of tablesorter - the original tablesorter does not have this option.

