The example contains

    int x = model.get_const_interp(decl);

This is not how models work. A model assigns an `expr` to every constant (and other things), and the automatic cast from `expr` to `int` is misleading; there exists an automatic conversion to `bool` (see `ast::operator bool`) and then another one from `bool` to `int` (in the C++ standard/compiler), which is why it returns `1` (non-zero pointer casted to bool 1 then casted to int 1). In this case, a warning or error message would be helpful, but I'm not sure we can do that and at the same time keep `ast::operator bool`.

The output of `get_const_interp(...)` will usually be a numeral (can be checked via `.is_numeral()`) and we need to get the `int` out of the numeral `expr`, for instance like so

    z3::expr x = model.get_const_interp(decl);
    std::cout << x << std::endl; // OK, 16.

    int xi;
    Z3_get_numeral_int(x.ctx(), x, &xi);
    std:: cout << xi << std::endl; // Now xi is also 16.

